</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=limpylionbait>LimpyLionBait</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Conjurer</span><br>  Posts: 294<br> <font color=#333333>(3/3/03 10:44:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8951.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Easy....</span><hr size=1> Sometimes simply running through your pet is enough to glom the add onto pet and off you.<br>
<br>
If that fails, stay very close to your pet and target the add, and alternate spamming your pet back off key and pet attack key - your pet will turn a bit and send a taunt to the add (or even smack it a few times) and then you back off with both mobs on pet. <br>
<br>
Mages need to be careful in dungeons or closed spaces - if you're unsure what may come around the corner always line yourself up behind the pet, so that any adds will encounter your pet first while its fighting the original mob. They will usually add onto pet instead of you.<br>
<br>
Get using to taking a pounding every now and then - if you avoid it at all costs its more shocking later and you may panic and die - -a cool head gained from experience will help you survive adds later.  <br>
<br>
For many levels I wouldnt let myself get hit ever - thought I was doing great :P Then the time would come when I had a few adds and no matter what I would gate or run for a zone - even when it was not totally necessary, because I didnt know what the limits were that I could fight to and still survive. <br>
<br>
Now I will do anything I can to avoid fleeing. If I have to kite all the adds around while pet kills first one, then latches onto mob 2, then 3, with me doing drive by healings or nukes, or use terrain to my advantage (yay for levitation - run off a hill top and out then circle around - the mobs loses alot of ground while you dont), etc. The higher level you get the harder it gets of course - you cant shrug off a quad hitting 150 mob very easily - you are after all wearing a robe :P Your tactics run more towards shifting adds to pet at all costs, then chain casting pets on the group until its more manageable. <br>
<br>
You'll have other items by then which will help you out - ie sow potions, jboots, scars of sigil (/hug), stun totems, snare and root items, blinding items, wands with instant dd charges, etc.<br>
<br>
Personally I have the phantom armor ac / regen line up at all times - this alone has saved me more times than I can count.<br>
<br>
Good hunting to you!<br>
Limpy<br>
